def: Having (such) a nature, temper, or disposition; disposed; --used in composition; as, good-natured, ill-natured, etc.
Not concealable. "Inconcealable imperfections." Sir T. Browne.
A large anchor stowed on shores outside the waist of a vessel;-- called also waist anchor. See the Note under Anchor.
The striped quagga, or Burchell's zebra, of South Africa(Asinus Burchellii); -- called also peechi, or peetsi.
One who makes boots.-- Boot"mak`ing, n.
To deceive or lead astray with a false light. Herrick.

A medium of great elasticity and extreme tenuity, supposed topervade all space, the interior of solid bodies not excepted, and tobe the medium of transmission of light and heat; hence often calledluminiferous ether.
Ability or capacity to write. [R.] Walpole.
Marked with spots and patches of white and some color otherthan black; -- usually distinguished from piebald, in which thecolors are properly white and black. Said of horses.
To open; to expand; to become disclosed or developed.The wind blows cold While the morning doth unfold. J. Fletcher.
